article.description: Liz Podominick scored 20 points and Janel McCarville had 14 to lead Minnesota (No. 17 ESPN/USA Today, No. 18 AP) past Creighton 79-71.
article.headline: Creighton closes in but can't overcome early deficit
article.linkText: Podominick, McCarville help Minnesota hold on
article.story:
OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- There's certainly more to Minnesota's inside game than All-America Janel McCarville.

Although McCarville was impressive, it was reserve post Liz Podominick who led the way with 20 points to spark the Golden Gophers (No. 17 ESPN/USA Today, No. 18 AP) to a 79-71 victory over Creighton on Sunday.

"We need her to come off the bench and be a dominant force like she was today," Minnesota coach Pam Borton said after Podominick had a career high in scoring and went 7-of-8 from the field, missing only her last shot.

McCarville and Jamie Broback added 14 points apiece and Kelly Roysland and April Calhoun had 10 each for the Golden Gophers (4-1).

Angie Janis scored 19 points, Laura Spanheimer 16 and Kristi Woodard 15 for the Bluejays (2-2).

Minnesota trailed 10-8 when Podominick and Shannon Schonrock hit back-to-back 3-pointers to start the first of two 11-0 runs in the first half. They also closed the half with 11 straight points, capped by another 3-pointer by Podominick, to lead 34-19.

"The last three minutes of the first half killed us," Creighton coach Jim Flanery said. "If we'd only been down five or seven points, it would have been a different game, you'd think."

Creighton eventually fell behind by 54-30 before rallying behind a strong inside game. The Bluejays closed to 67-60 with 4:14 to play on a 3-pointer by Woodard. But six straight points, four on free throws, by McCarville put the Gophers up by 13 to offset a 7-0 run by the Bluejays.

Minnesota used six free throws, four by Broback and two by Roysland, in the final 38 seconds to keep Creighton at bay.

Borton liked what she saw in the first 25 minutes and Podominick was at a loss for words when asked to describe the second half.

"I don't know what happened," she said, "but we were able to make the key plays at the end."

Minnesota, which defeated Creighton 82-71 in Minneapolis last season, handed the Bluejays their 12th straight loss against ranked opponents.

McCarville also grabbed nine rebounds, dished out seven assists and had four blocks. She affected several other shots, particularly in the first half when Creighton shot 31 percent (9-of-29).

Creighton finished at 48 percent (30-63) with its strong second half that resulted in 52 points. The Gophers shot 54 percent (26-48) and had a 35-26 rebounding advantage.

The Gophers limited Creighton to only four 3-point attempts. The Bluejays have been attempting more than 30 per game.

"They came out and changed their complete game plan," Borton said. "We played great basketball in the first 25 minutes, but I think that's the worst half I've ever seen Creighton play."

The comeback, though it fell short, may have a positive effect down the road.

"It gives us confidence knowing we can play with any team in the country," Creighton's Amy Hoffman said.
